<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9113&amp;p=97249#p97249"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">cak wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />In regard to microtuning, I think extra flats/sharps would be more flexible than extra note letters.<br /></div>You still can use flats/sharps but simply - is down one and + is up one so if there are more spaces between the letters then you may need more than one sharps/flats to access some notes. However, due to the playback engine there is only up to sixteen notes in one octave regardless of what each letter corresponds to and what frequencies (or periods) are used for each note of an octave. (For example, c+-++-++-- is also a C sharp note same as c+ is, and if the scale you set has three extra unnamed notes between the "c" and "d" then you would need double flat/sharp like c++ or d-- to access the note in between.)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4734">zzo38</a> — Sat Jul 28, 2012 10:55 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
